Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update (please note that there has been consistent weekend reporting artifact since the presentation of these data began):
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 54.9% of the global newly reported cases and 50.1% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. The USA reported 46.1% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, and Brazil reported 27.5%, Mexico 4.9%, Colombia 3.9%, Peru 3.8%, Chile 3.2%, and Argentina 2.6%. Basically the same countries in the same order. While Brazil had been reporting 30 000+ cases a day, the number of daily new cases is starting to decrease over the past week,

The European region reported 10.8% of the global newly reported cases and 12.1% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 34.1% of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Sweden 8.8%, Spain 6.7%, Kazakhstan 5.9%, Turkey 5.8%, France 4.5%, Israel 4.4%, Ukraine 3.0%, Azerbaijan 2.7%, and Kyrgyzstan 2.4%. These countries all merit keeping an eye on their case counts as the numbers of reported cases is increasing.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 9.8% of the global newly reported cases and 15.7% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 24.9% of the regional newly reported cases followed Pakistan by 15.9%, Iran 15.5%, Iraq 10.6%, Oman 9.2%, Egypt 5.7%, Kuwait 4.2%, Qatar 3.2%, and UAE 3.1%. Multiple countries are very active in the region -- same countries with some changes in the order since yesterday (6 Jul 2020).

The African region reported 7.3% of the global newly reported cases and 4.8% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 71.0% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Cote d'Ivoire 5.7%, Nigeria 4.6%, Cameroon 3.9%, Algeria 3.7%, Madagascar 2.4%, and Ethiopia 2.2%. South Africa remains number 1 and other countries are varied. It appears as though Nigeria is slowing down in transmission. Of note is that South Africa reported almost 9000 cases today (7 Jul 2020).

The Western Pacific region reported 1.6% of the global newly reported cases and 0.29% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 76.8% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 7.6%, Singapore 6.8%, Australia 5.1%, South Korea 1.6%, and China 0.92%. The Philippines is consistently reporting the highest number of cases with Japan at number 2.

The South East Asia region reported 15.6% of the global newly reported cases and 17.1% of global deaths. India reported 82.8% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 11.9%, Indonesia 4.5%, and Nepal 0.67%. Same countries, same order as in previous days, with India continuing to be the driving force in the regional growth in cases.

Impression (unchanged): The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis, followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe and the Eastern Mediterranean alternating on a daily basis of their order, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily caseload of all of the regions. The Africa region is slowing increasing their representation in terms of increased case reporting.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 7 Jul 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South-East Asia, in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting.- Mod.MPP]

